    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey can u explain bernoulli's principle and how it actually works to make an airplane wing lift up? like what's the deal with the shape of the airfoil?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Bernoulli's principle states that an increase in an object's speed occurs simultaneously with a decrease in pressure or a decrease in the object's potential energy. For airplane wings, the airfoil shape is designed so that the top surface is curved and the bottom is flatter. As the airplane moves forward, air flows faster over the top surface of the wing than underneath. According to Bernoulli's principle, this faster airflow over the top decreases the air pressure atop the wing, while the slower, denser air on the bottom keeps the pressure higher. This pressure difference creates an upward force, known as lift, that supports the aircraft in the air.",
      "source": "target",
