    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense, but i'm still a bit confused about how the air \"knows\" to go faster on top. like, is there something physical pushing it or is it just because of the curve? and what about the air underneath, does it have to do with the angle of the wing too?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The \"knowing\" you're referring to is essentially the physics of fluid dynamics. When air flows over a curved surface, like a wing, it moves closer to the surface of the wing and has to travel a shorter distance than what it would on a straight path. This means that to cover the shorter distance in a given time (as air moves over the wing), it must speed up. This is intuitive when you see the wing in motion — the airplane must constantly move forward, so the air can't travel infinitely, it tilts and speeds up.\n\n\nAs for the air underneath the wing, it is influenced by both the shape of the airfoil and the angle of attack, which is the angle between the wing and the oncoming air. Generally, the angle of attack can increase lift to a point until the airflow underneath the wing stalls, at which point lift dramatically decreases. The air's tendency to accelerate over the curved surface is designed so it complements the wing's angle of attack, helping generate lift. So, it's a combination of shape (causing the air to accelerate over one side of the wing) and the angle of attack (leaning the wing as much as possible within design limits) that helps determine the air's behavior and directs",
      "source": "target",
